column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT A&W PLANT FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES WHEN HOSE RUPTURED ABOUT 12" FROM VALVE, SPRAYING OVER THE VALVE.  DRIVER PANICKED. RATHER THAN USING THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE, HE SHUT OFF THE AIR TO THE TANK THEN TURNED OFF THE UNLOADING VALVE.  BY THE TIME VALVE WAS TURNED OFF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT PIT. A COMMUNICATION HAS BEEN SENT FROM OUR GENERAL OFFICE TO OUR TERMINALS INSTRUCTING THE MANAGERS TO RE-TRAIN ALL DRIVERS IN THE PROPER OPERATION OF THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE.

driver attempted to clear his unloading hose and customer's plumbing, by blowing air through the unloading hose.  when the lines were clear the driver shut off the air flow and there was a siphon effect, which caused the product to flow back through the lines out a small pressure relief valve.  there was approximately 5 gallons spilled before driver could shut the relief valve. in the future we will request an ocean spray employee to operate and close their valve when all lines are clear.

SMELLED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 76803 ON TRACK #64 CLASSIFICATION.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY CONRAIL SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. MILLER, REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO THE ELIZABETH, N.J. GENERAL MEDICAL CENTER AND EXAMIANED BY DR.  CABANO AND RELEASED.  NO LOST TIME OR MEDICATION PRESCRIBED.

column168: A HOWELL TRANSPORTATION TEAM DISPATCHED FROM SAN ANTONIO TO PICK UP IN LAKE CHARLES AT A PP&G PLANT WERE INVOLVED IN A SERIOUS PACKAGING INCIDENT. ALL NECESSARY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED INCLUDING THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, CHEMTREC, GEORGIA DOT AND GEORGIA EPA.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED-UP BY AN ENSITE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.

FLOOR DRY AND ABSORBENTS WERE USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL INSIDE THE TRAILER AS WELL AS WHAT HAD ESCAPED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRIALER, THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED, ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL USED WAS PLACED INSIDE THE OVERPACK AND DISPOSED OF ALONG WITH THE DRUM. THE LEAKING CONTAINER HAD A SHINY PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM INDICATING A FRESH OPENING POSSIBLY CAUSED DURING LOADING.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE CONTAINER.  HAZMAT'S DRIVER WAS NOT PRESENT DURING LOADING.  NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.

column168: TRAIN HAZB6 (SULFURIC ACID UNIT TRAIN), TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND THROUGH NORTH BERGEN YARD ON YARD ON TRACK #2, DERAILED AT APPROXIMATELY 2215 HOURS ON 2/27/91.  DERAILMENT INVOLVED TRAIN POSITIONS 16-22.  ALL TANKS CARS (111A100W2)) IN TRAIN CONTAINED SULFURIC ACID, AND CARS WERE EQUIPPED WITH BOTTOM OUTLETS, UNDER AUTHORITY OF CANADIAN TRANSPORT COMMISSION SPECIAL PERMIT 2178 AND DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION EXEMPTION (DOT-E) 9657.  TANK CAR PROX 13539 (#16), PROX 13504 (#21) AND PROX 13503 (#22) WERE UPRIGHT IN LINE WITH ONLY ONE TRUCK DERAILED.  TANK CARS PROX 13508, 13518, 13538 AND 13502 (CARS 17-20) AND DERAILED, AND WERE LEAKING TO THE EAST SIDE OF THE TRACK, AGAINST CONRAIL ENGINE 1900 AND CABOOSE CR 24521.  TANK CARS 17 THROUGH 20 SUSTAINED EXTENSIVE JACKET DAMAGE ON THE EAST SIDE (OR SIDE AGAINST THE LOCOMOTIVE) HOWEVER, OTHER THAN JACKET DAMAGE, ALL SHELLS OF THE TANKS WERE NOTED TO BE INTACT, WITH NO SCRAPED, DENTS, ETC.  AN INSPECTION OF ALL VALVE AND CLOSURES WAS ACCOMPLISHED PRIOR TO RERAILING. SOME LEAKAGE WAS EVIDENT ON PROX 13502, ORIGINATING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, PROBABLY OCCURRING DURING THE DERAILMENT.  ALL OTHER CARS WERE SECURE.  RERAILING WAS COMPLETED AT 1400 HOURS 2/28/91.  TOTAL ESTIMATED COST OF DERAILMENT - $35,000.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH PERIDOT TO TRANSFER THE SULFURIC ACID AS FOLLOWS: PROX 13508 INTO UTLX 11823 PROX 13518 INTO PLMX 721 PROX 13538 INTO UTLX 15105 PROX 13502 INTO UTLX 1620

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE SECONDARY AREA. THE COVER POPPED UP ON ONE SIDE AND IT LEAKED ONTO ABOUT 20 OTHER PACKAGES.  THOSE PACKAGES WERE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED TO THEIR CONSIGNEES.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE'S COVER WAS TIGHTENED AND THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  ALL DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.  A COPY OF THIS REPORT IS BEING SENT TO THE ORIGIN CUSTOMER SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE FOR FOLLOW-UP.

OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER THEN COLLIDED WITH THE AUTOMOBILE CAUSING IT TO LEAVE THE ROADWAY, STRIKING A HIGHWAY SIGN AND PROCEEDING THROUGH A FENCE.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER THEN OVERTURNED AND BURST INTO FLAMES IN A PASTURE ADJACENT TO AL. HWY 10.  THE AUTOMOBILE CAME TO A FINAL REST IN THE WESTBOUND LANE OF AL. HWY 10 AND ALSO BURST INTO FLAMES. THE PEOPLE IN BOTH THE AUTOMOBILE AND OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER WERE UNABLE TO EXIT THE VEHICLES BEFORE BEING CONSUMED IN THE FIRES, RESULTING IN THREE FATALITIES.  OUR SAFETY ADMINISTRATOR WENT TO THE SCENE.  OUR PRESIDENT NOTIFIED DOT IN ATLANTA WITHIN 24 HOURS. OUR SAFETY PERSON ON THE SCENE ASSISTED STATE TROOPERS, FIREMEN AND THE ON SCENE COMMANDER IN OBTAINING INFORMATION ABOUT THE DRIVER, INSURANCE, TRAILER CONTENTS, ETC.  HE ALSO CALLED AN EMERGENCY TEAM IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE (ACTION, FROM MONTGOMERY).  DOT AND STATE TROOPERS DID NOT FAULT OUR DRIVER NOR FIND ANY DISCREPANCIES.  THE MESS WAS CLEANED UP.  SEE ATTACHMENTS.

column168: WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY LOCATION HE WAS TOLD BY THE SECRETARY TO DRIVE AROUND BEHIND THE BUILDING AND THAT SOMEONE WOULD MEET HIM. OUR DRIVER WAS MET BY MR. column168: VII & VIII ABOVE: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE OF ANY KIND ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. THIS INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF OUR DRIVER'S ERROR.  OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL AT THE SERVICE STATION AT THE SAME TIME.  THE DRIVER STATES THAT HE WAS WATCHING THE GASOLINE DELIVERY AND WHEN HE TURNED AROUND, HE SAW DIESEL FUEL COMING OUT OF THE STICK HOLE FOR THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE FLOW OF FUEL WHICH HAD RUN ONTO SOME GRASS, BLACKTOP AND INTO A CATCH BASIN.  A SPILL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN & THEY VACUUMED OUT THE CATCH BASIN AND CLEANED UP THE OTHER AFFECTED AREAS.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY ASSIGNED A REFERENCE # 9011551 TO THE INCIDENT.  OUR DRIVER WAS IMMEDIATELY SUSPENDED AND MAY BE TERMINATED PENDING REVIEW OF HIS FILE. column168: THE BARRELL WAS LOADED NEAR THE FRONT OF OUR TRAILER. EMPLOYEE JERRY DAY WAS LOADING A PALLET BEHIND THE BARRELL.  FORKS WERE STICKING THROUGH THE PALLET AND JERRY PUNCTURED THE BARRELL ABOUT ONE FOOT ABOVE FLOOR LEVEL. THE LEAKING BARRELL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AS SOON AS THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND ALL OTHER SHIPMENTS WERE SECURED.  SEVERAL SHEETS OF CARDBOARD AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE PAINT ON TRAILER FLOOR.  AS MUCH PAINT AS POSSIBLE WAS SQUEEGEED FROM TRAILER FLOOR INTO THE RECOVERY DRUM.  THE CARDBOARD AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS ALLOWED TO DRY OUTSIDE.  WE HAVE BEEN ADVISED TO DISPOSE OF THIS MATERIAL BY NORMAL TRASH COLLECTION BY THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  A CORRECTIVE LETTER WILL BE ISSUED TO DRIVER DAY EXPLAINING HIS LACK OF PROPER CARE AND HANDLING OF MATERIALS INVOLVED.  THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS AN EXAMPLE TO ALL OTHER EMPLOYEES IN THIS UNIT AS A REMAINDER OF PROPER AND CAREFUL LOADING PROCEDURES PARTICULARLY REGARDING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE RECOVERED PORTION OF THIS SHIPMENT WAS SENT ON TO DELIVER PER THE SHIPPER.

THE CHECKED ARTICLES ALONG WITH MR SAMPSON WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT IN DENVER.  A TOTAL OF SEVEN OTHER PASSENGER BAGS CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LIQUID.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 11-1671, DOCKMAN, JACK RUDDY, SPEARED ONE FIVE GALLON DRUM.  THE SKID ON WHICH THE DRUM WAS LOCATED HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF A ROUND PIECE OF STEEL AND WAS LEANING BACKWARDS.  WHEN MR RUDDY POSITIONED HIS FORKS ON THE JEEP, HE WAS OPERATING UNDER THE SKID.  HE SPEARED THE CAN DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE SKID.  MR RUDDY REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUM FROM THE SKID TO PREVENT COMPLETE DRAINAGE OF THE DRUM.  HE THEN PUT OIL DRY ON THE SPILL TO ABSORB THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  MR.  RUDDY THEN NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED.  HERITAGE INDUSTRIES HAS BEEN CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION OF THE DRUM.

column25: U S GOVT - DEFENSE FUEL REGION
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELLING WEST BOUND ON U.S. 42 NEAR SEALEYVILLE, INDIANA IN A DENSE FOG.  THE VEHICLE CAME UPON ROAD SIGNS INDICATING AN UPCOMING 90 DEGREE TURN TO THE LEFT.  THE DRIVER APPLIED BRAKES, THE WHEELS ON THE TRAILER LOACKED, IT LEFT THE ROAD SURFACE TO THE RIGHT AND STARTED THE ROLL-OVR.  TWO ROAD SIGNS AND A UTILITY POLE WERE DAMAGED BEFORE THE UNIT CAME TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE ON THE ROAD SURFACE IN THE 90 DEGREE TURN, THE OVER-FILL PROTECTION PROBE IN THE DOME CLOSURE WAS FORCED OUT ALLOWING APPROX.  4100 GALLONS OF AVIATION FUEL TO ESCAPE (SEE ATTACHED FOR DIAGRAM OF PRODUCT FLOW AND RECOVERY EFFORTS).  SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA IS BEING UTILIZED IN THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP EFFORTS THIS WORK IS BEING OVERSEEN BY THE INDIANA DEPARTMETN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT.  40 CUBIC YARDS OF CONTAINMANTED SOUIL IS BEING HELD ON SIGHT IN HAZ-MAT ROLL-OFF BOXES AWAITING ANALYTICAL RESULTS FOR DISPOSAL. AN EVACUATION OF 2 RESIDENCES AND ONE BUSINESS INVOLVING 10 PEOPLE WAS EXECUTED WHILE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES WERE TAKING PLACE.  US 42 AND 1 BUSINESS REAMINED CLOSE FOR APPROX. 8 HOURS UNTIL THE AREA HAD BENN DEEMED SECURED AND CLEAR FOR PASSAGE BY THE INDIANA STATE HIGHWAY PATROL.  NO INJURIES HAVE RESULTED DUE TO THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  THE VIGO COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT IS MONITORING ALL WELLS INT HE AREA OF THE SPILL FOR SIGNS OF CONTAMINATION, NO SIGNS OF NAY PROBLEMS AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT.  CONVERSATIONS WITH JIM REDICKS, ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SPECIALIST FOR THE VIRGO COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT HAVE LEAD US TO BELIEVE HE HAS NOT OBSERVED ANY VISIBLE AREAS THAT MAY CONTAMINATE WELLS.

SHIPMENT TRANSFERRED AT CARLISLE BY JAMES ORNER.  RECOUPED BY GREY NEIFERT. RECOUPED WEARING PROTECTIVE APPARATUS.  SOME ODER OF MATERIAL WAS DETECTED BY JAMES ORNER BEFORE DAMAGE WAS NOTICED.

OUR DRIVER, SCOTT SCHMIDT, PULLED INTO THE SERVICE STATION OFF I-80 E.B. MILE POST 145 AND STOPPED.  AT THIS TIME, ANOTHER DRIVER CAME OVER THE CB AND TOLD SCOTT SOMETHING LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER, FOUND THE LEAK AND CALLED BOB BRINK INC.  WHILE HE WAS CALLING, THE INDIANA STATE POLICE CAME.  SCOTT WENT TO THEM AND ASKED WHAT THEY WANTED HIM TO DO.  THE MADE HIM SIT IN A PATROL CAR.  IN THE MEANTIME, BOB BRINK INC. CALLED THE SHIPPER (3M) AND THEY CALLED IN A CLEAN UP CREW.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE PARKING LOT OF THE SERVICE STATION.  (SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS).  SERGEANT HEDGES OF THE INDIANA STATE POLICE CHECKED THE ENTRANCE RAMP FOR DRIPPINGS AND FOUND NONE.  DUE TO THE CHEMICAL XYLENE FOUND IN THE LIQUID, THE POLICE CLOSED THE ENTRANCE RAMP TO THE SERVICE STATION, PLUS, EVACUATED THE GAS STATION AND RESTAURANT LOCATED THERE FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS.  IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE OUT OF TEN 55 GALLON DRUMS WAS LEAKING, DUE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM BEING RUSTED THROUGH.  A DAM OF SAND WAS FORMED TO CONFINE THE DRIPPING LIQUID.  THE CONTAMINATED SAND, SUPPLIES AND LEAKING DRUM WERE PUT INTO SALVAGE DRUMS TO BE RETURNED TO 3-M OF BROWNWOOD, TX.  3-M HAS ASSURED US THIS WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. ALSO, ALL OUR DRIVER HAD BEEN INFORMED NOT TO PICK UP DRUMS CONTAINING ANY RUST.

column42: METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE, IN SOLUTION WITH NOT MORE THAN 9% BY WEIGHT ACTIVE OXYGEN
column168: ON 02-15-91, AT APPROXIMATELY 02:00 HRS., I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR FOR ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER RIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO  45177, INVESTIGATED A SPILL IN BUILDING C OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS A FIBREBOARD BOX THAT WAS WET.  UPON ARRIVAL, I FOUND THE BOX TO BE OF FIBREBOARD.  IT HAD ARROWS INDICATING ORIENTATION DRAWN ON IT WITH A BLACK, PERMANENT MARKER.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE BOX.  THERE WERE NO SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THE BOX.  THERE WAS A PACKING SLIP AND AN INVOICE ATTACHED TO THE BOX WHICH INDICATED THE BOX CONTAINED 500 2 OZ. BOTTLES OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE.  UPON OPENING THE BOX, I FOUND 500 PLASTIC BOTTLES LABELED "HARDENER", EACH OF 2 OZ.  THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON ANY OF THESE INNER BOTTLES.  THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS WET ON ONE SIDE.  I ESTIMATE 1 OZ. OF THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN OUR HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  ONCE THE SHIPMENT HAS BEEN RELEASED, IT WILL BE TRUCKED TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.

column168: LEAKING TANK CAR NATX 16494, SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION ON SUNDAY, FEBRUARY 25, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS, ACCA YARD ASSIGNMENT AR-6 DISCOVERED TANK CAR NATX 16494 LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO THE YARDMASTER AND THE CAR WAS PLACED IN NO. 20 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD WHERE IT WAS ISOLATED UNTIL REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. MR. T. W. GRUBBS, SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, FOR RF&P WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING, AND ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT APPROXIMATELY 1750 HOURS.  HE MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR AND FOUND IT WAS NOT LEAKING ON HIS ARRIVAL, BUT IT HAD BEEN LEAKING WHEN IN MOTION FROM AROUND THE AREA OF THE FITTINGS WHICH CONTAINED THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC. MR. GRUBBS CONTACTED WILLIAM H. OERTLY, JR., DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE ASSOCIATED OF AMERICAN RAILROADS, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, AT 1810 HOURS AND MR. OERTLY ADVISED HE WOULD BE AT ACCA YARD AT 1900 HOURS TO REPAIR THE TANK CAR.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1820 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, MORTON INTERNATIONAL OF ELMA, WASHINGTON. MR. OERTLY ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT 1900 HOURS, AND WHEN AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE TANK CAR, THE CAUSE FOR THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 1915 HOURS. THE CAR WAS PLACED BACK INTO RAIL SERVICE AT 1930 HOURS. THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE, MR. DICK WALKER, PRODUCTION MANAGER FOR MORTON INTERNATIONAL, CALLED BACK AT 2100 HOURS AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED.

THE LOAD WAS QUICKLY ISOLATED TO BELEN RIVER TRACK, 7407, WHERE REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED PROMPTLY AND MR. LARRY FORTENBERRY DISPATCHED TERRA INTERNATIONAL PERSONNEL TO BELEN TO ARREST THE LEAK AND MAKE REPAIRS AS NECESSARY.  CLOSE INSPECTION REVEALED MATERIAL ESCAPING FROM THE "A" END OF THE DOME COVER FROM A LOADING VALVE. APPARENTLY, AT THE LOADING POINT, A TWO INCH PIPE PLUG WAS CROSS THREADED WHEN IT WAS INSTALLED, WHICH ALLOWED THE LEAKAGE.  THE TERRA PERSONNEL REMOVED THE PLUG AND A 2X3 INCK NIPPLE APPLIED, REDRESSED THE THREADS AND MADE A PROPER REINSTALLATION.  THESE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 10:00 AM ON FEBRUARY 4, 1991.  OTHER REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE TANKER'S HANDHOLDS BY EQUIPMENT DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL.

OUR TRUCK #T134 AND CARGO TANK # LBT929 WITH DRIVER MR. KEVIN BARKER, LOADED AT THE BP OIL LIMA REFINERY. THE PERSONNEL EMPLOYED BY PATCHEM, WORKING FOR BP OIL LOADED OUR VEHICLE. PATCHEM PERSONNEL HAVE IN THE PAST PERFORMED ALL LOADING FUNCTIONS WHICH INCLUDED CLOSING ALL VALVES, CAPS AND DOME COVERD AND OUR DRIVERS WOULD PERFORM A WALK AROUND INSPECTION PRIOR TO LEAVING THE SHIPPERS.  THE DRIVER IN THIS CASE DID PERFORM A WALKAROUND INSPECTION BUT FAILED TO CHECK THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK.  ONCE LOADED, OUR VEHICLE LEFT THE LOADING AREA AND PROCEEDED ONTO THE PUBLIC HIGHWAY TO GO TO THE SCALES TO BE WEIGHED.  AT THE FIRST INTERSECTION (BUCKEYE RD.  AND S DIXIE HWY) APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE FROM THE LOADING AREA, OUR VEHICEL STOPPED AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT.  UPON ACCELERATION AND TURNING ONTO S DIXIE OUR DRIVER NOTICED LEAKAGE ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  HE PULLED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO INSPECT THE CARGO AND FOUND THAT THE REAR FUSIBLE CAP HAD NOT BEEN INSTALLED AND APPROXIMATELY THREE (3) POUNDS OR LESS THAN ONE HALF (1/2) A GALLON OF WASTE WAS SPILLED.  HE INSTALLED THE CAP, THEN RETURNED TO THE LOADING AREA.  HE NOTIFIED THE PATCHEM PERSONNEL AT THE LAODING AREA AND THEY IN TURN NOTIFIED BP OIL.   A CREW FROM BP OIL RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT TO CLEANUP THE WASTE.  THE WASTE WAS SCRAPED UP INTO A BUCKET AND RETURNED TO THE LOADING AREA.  THE WASTE WAS SCRAPED UP INTO A BUCKET AND RETURNED TO THE LOADING AREA.  CALLS TO REPORT THE SPILL, AS NOTED ABOVE, WERE PLACED. THE PERSONNEL INVOLVED  WITH THIS PROJECT WERE ALERT TO INSEPCT ALL VALVES, CAPS, AND DOME COVERS PRIOR TO LEAVING.  THE DRIVER WAS WARNED ABOUT PERFORMING AN IMPROPER WALKAROUD INSPECTION BUT NOT LOOKING ON TOP OF THE TANK FOR UNSAFE CONDITIONS.  THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT IS BEING ATTRIBUTED TO DRIVER ERROR.  ALL DRIVERS RECEIVED NOTICES ALERTING THEM OF THE INCIDENT AND THE CAUSE.  THE SHIPPER HAS DONE THE SAME WITH THEIR PERSONNEL WORKING IN THE AREA. (MEI TRANSPORTATION 030191).

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON THE EARLY MORNING OF FEBRUARY 2, 1991, APPROXIMATELY 6:00 A.M., A HTS TEAM DISPATCHED FROM SAN ANTONIO TO HAMTRAMIK, MICHIGAN HAD AN APPARENT BRAKE FIRE. THEY WERE TRAVELING I-35 AND WERE IN THE GENERAL AREA OF WAXIHACHIE JUST SOUTH OF DALLAS, TEXAS. WHEN JOE LLAMAS NOTICED THE PROBLEM HE EXITED OFF ON EXIT 399 AND BOTH DRIVERS BEGAN TRYING TO PUT OUT THE BLAZE WITH THEIR EXTINGUISHERS WHICH LASTED ABOUT 5 MINUTES. WHEN THE EXTINGUISHERS WERE EMPTIED THE FIRE CONTINUED TO BLAZE. THE TRAILERS RIGHT REAR TIRES THEN CAUGHT ON FIRE. WHEN THE DRIVERS REALIZED THE SITUATION WAS GETTING OUT OF CONTROL THEY VACATED THE AREA AND TRIED TO KEEP PASSERSBY AWAY FROM THE UNIT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED IN ABOUT 10 MINUTES, JUST IN TIME TO EXTINGUISH THE BLAZE AND PREVENT A SERIOUS ACCIDENT. THE CALLER TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME. THE DRIVERS HAD JUST PERFORMED A TIRE CHECK ABOUT 20 MINUTES PREVIOUS TO THIS AND EVERYTHING WAS OKAY. IT IS SPECULATED THE RIGHT REAR BRAKE DID NOT COMPLETELY RELEASE, WHICH BUILT UP FRICTION, STARTING THE FIRE.

CYLINDERS WERE PUT INTO A MTY TRLS AND CLOSED. ATTEMPTED TO GET MSDS FROM MATHESON GAS BUT THEY WERE CLOSED.  CONTACTED CHEMTREC & BILL BUGLIO-SAFETY SUPERVISOR, CCX MATHESON CAME OUT NEXT DAY 2-22-91 AND REPLACED VALVES ON CYLINDERS AND FOUND NO LEAK AT TIME.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: DRIVER WAS TRANSFERRING LOAD VIA TRANSFER LINES AT THE PIT AREA OF K.A. STEEL CHEMICALS, FROM HIS TRUCK TO A ROGERS CARTAGE TRUCK.  DRIVER WALKED AWAY FROM HIS TRUCK TO THE RESTROOM (ABOUT 100') AND WAS NOT ATTENDING THE OFF LOADING AS HE SHOULD.  BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD GET BACK TO HIS TRUCK THE TRAILER WENT EMPTY AND THE AIR PRESSURE IN THE LINES BLEW THE PRODUCT UP THROUGH THE OPEN DOME OF THE ROGERS TRAILER.  THE K.A. STEEL PLANT PERSONNEL FLUSHED THE SPILLAGE INTO OUR PIT AT THE TRANSFER SITE.  THEY USED A BOB CAT TO TAKE UP THE GRAVEL AND DIRT AND PUT IT IN OUR IRON OXIDE BOX.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO ANY WATERWAY.  DRIVER TO BE REPRIMANDED AND GIVEN TIME OFF FOR HIS NEGLIGENCE.  LETTER POSTED TO ALL DRIVERS REMINDING THEM THAT THEY MUST BE WITHIN 25' OF THEIR TRUCKS AT ALL TIMES WHILE LOADING OR OFFLOADING.  NAC#60867

ON 02/24/91, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM H. SMITH WAS NOTIFIED BY PORT LAREDO THAT A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE LOADING AREA OF THE INTERMODAL TANK.  SSA/HM SMITH'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC AND PAUL STEDMAN OF ATOCHEM RESPONDED WITH REPLACEMENT GASKET MATERIAL.  GASKET WAS REPLACED AND INTERMODAL WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column62: Overfilled; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) L D LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT COMPANY THAT CONTAINER APLS 276354, LOADED WITH 80 DRUMS OF XYLENE WAS LEAKING AT BOTTOM LEFT REAR CORNER OF THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER.  CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND SSA/HM LIBBY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED STEEL DRUM CRUSHED ENOUGH TO OPEN THE SIDE SEAM.  SSA/HM LIBBY CONTACTED  (MIKE HILL) AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES AND NOTIFIED HIM THAT IMPROPER LOADING AND OVER PACKING WERE SUSPECTED.  SSA/HM LIBBY ALSO CONTACTED RUSS DRUMMOND, ARTIC PACKAGING INTO 40 FOOT CONTAINER APLU 802435 ALONG WITH THE ONE OVERPACKED DAMAGED DRUM AND RELEASED OR DELIVERY.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL K.C. DECHANT (DSA/HM) WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR GATX 27001 WAS LEAKING WITH VAPORIZATION VISIBLE. THE TOPEKA FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE AND UNABLE TO DETERMINE EXACT SOURCE OF LEAK AND ORDERED EVACUATION OF THREE NEARBY BUSINESSES. TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED BY BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTORS, ALAN MATY AND BOB EWOLDT, AND DSA/HM K. DECHANT.  LEAKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE FROM GASKETED AREA BETWEEN FILL HOLE AND BLIND FLANGE AND THE VAPOR VALVE MOUNTING BOLT WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE LOOSE. THE FILL HOLE FLANGE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND ALL FITTINGS FULLY TIGHTENED. TANK CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INDUCE A PRODUCT SURGE TO TEST FITTINGS FOR TIGHTNESS.  NO LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED. TOPEKA FIRE DEPARTMENT, TOPEKA POLICE DEPARTMENT AND KANSAS STATE ENVIRONMENTAL WERE ALL ON SCENE.  SHIPPER (GERALD MARTIN) WAS CONTACTED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Over-pressurized
column168: DRIVER HAD JUST LOADED WASTE MATERIAL INTO HIS TANK TRAILER AT CUSTOMER'S (CHERRY TEXTRON'S) PLACE OF BUSINESS.  HE PULLED TRUCK OUT OF DRIVEWAY ONTO MILLER STREET.  AT THE FIRST APPLICATION OF THE BRAKES, HE NOTICED A MILKY FLUID SPRAY ACROSS THE TOP OF HIS CAB.  HE PULLED OVER IMMEDIATELY, TO FIND THAT A "BLEEDER VALVE" ON TOP OF THE TANK WAS STUCK IN THE OPEN POSITION AND THAT SOME AMOUNT OF FLUID HAD ESCAPED IN A SPRAY--THEN ACCUMULATING IN THE RIGHT-HAND GUTTER NEAR HIS TRUCK.  MATERIAL WAS DIKED WITH SOIL.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM OUR OWN COMPANY, WHO DILUTED, PRESSURE-WASHED THE AREA, AND PUMPED DILUTED WASTE INTO 2ND TANK TRAILER FROM THE CO. (AT THE SAME CLIENT'S ADDRESS).  MATERIAL TAKEN ON TO ORIGINAL TSDF (NORRIS INDUSTRIES).

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DEAN COOPER WAS NOTIFIED THAT UTLX 756 WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE LOS ANGELES SWITCHING YARD.  SSA/HM COOPERS INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE DUAL COMPARTMENT TYPE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLETS.  EACH COMPARTMENT HAD A BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND BOTH BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVES WERE NOT FULLY SEATING TO SECURE THE PRODUCT.  SSA/HM COOPER ALSO FOUND BOTH BOTTOM OUTLET CAPS LOOSE, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO DRIP TO THE GROUND.  BOTH OUTLET CAPS AND VALVES WERE TIGHTENED/RESEATED WHICH STOPPED ALL FLOW OF PRODUCT.

column42: PHOSPHORUS WHITE OR YELLOW, IN WATER
column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON FEBRUARY 20, 1991 AT APPROXIMATELY 1110, TRAIN NPNL 19 DERAILED NEAR MILE POST 19.25 THE RIVER SUBDIVISION BETWEEN BOONEVILLE AND WOOLDRIDGE, MISSOURI.  CREW REPORTED THAT A PLUME OF SMOKE WAS COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE PHOSPHOROUS TANK CARS. TANK CAR GATX 14948 HAD RAIL PUNCTURE TO THE TANK CAR ON "B" END NEAR THE BOTTOM WITH PHOSPHOROUS ESCAPING ONTO THE GROUND AND LEAKING BETWEEN TANK AND OUTER INSULATION JACKET TOWARDS THE "A" END.  FIRE WAS BROUGHT UNDER CONTROL WITH FOAM APPLICATION. A METAL BOX WAS WELDED TO THE TANK CAR TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  TANK CAR WAS UPRIGHTED AND MOVED ACROSS THE RIGHT OF WAY FOR REMOVAL OF THE JACKET AND HOT WATER CLEANING OF THE TANK.  THE PHOSPHOROUS-CONTAMINATED JACKET WAS WASHED; THE CONTAMINATED INSULATION AND SURROUNDING EARTH WERE PLACED IN STEEL DRUMS FOR RECOVERY OF THE PHOSPHOROUS.  AFTER REMOVEAL OF THE JACKEY AND INSULATION, THE ENTIRE SURFACE OF THE TANK WAS HOT WATER WASHED TO REMOVE CONTAMINATION.  THE CAR WAS THEN LOADED ONTO A FLAT, AND MOVED VIA SPECIAL TRAIN TO FMC CORP., LAWRENCE, KANSAS FOR OFF-LOADING (REF. DOT-E 10557.

column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER/TRAIN-INDUSTRY OPERATIONS KEN PFAFF REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 84453 LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK (501) AND SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND INSPECTION DETERMINED A FAILED RUPTURE DISC.  SSA/HM ROQUET REPLACED FAILED RUPTURE DISC AND CHECKED ALL OTHER FITTINGS. THE SPILLED PRODUCT (ON TANK CAR) WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH VINEGAR AND CLEANED OFF OF THE CAR SURFACES.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  TRAIN MANAGEMENT AND CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

column62: Overfilled; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON 02/17/91, UNION PACIFIC BRAKEMAN, MANUEL BARRERA, WAS SWITCHING RAIL CARS WHEN GATX 52852 SPLASHED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON HIM.  MR. BERRARA IMMEDIATELY WASHED AFFECTED AREA WITH SOAP AND WATER.  MANAGER, MIKE METCALF WAS NOTIFIED AND MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS OFFERED AND REFUSED. GATX 52852 WAS INSPECTED BY CAR FOREMAN RUSSELL CAMPBELL.  MR. CAMPBELL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR FILL WAY TO BE IMPROPERLY SECURED WHICH ALLOWED A VOID IN THE GASKET SEAL AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND A SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED TO REPAIR THE GASKET AND SEAL THE CAR.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO BE FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

DARELL ALEN TRUCK DRIVER FOR SPEEDY INC. WAS LOADING HIS TRUCK FOR DELIVERIES MONDAY 2/4/91  HE BEGAN TO PUT THE FREIGHT ON A SKID SO HE COULD LOAD IT ON THE TRUCK HE PICKED UP ONE OF THE BOXES TO PUT ON SKID, THE BOX SLID APPROXIMATELY 6 TO 7 INCHES OUT OF HIS HAND TO THE SKID.
